Technical Architecture
Overview
The DarshanEase application follows a modern three-tier architecture consisting of the Presentation Layer, Application Layer, and Data Layer. This architecture ensures scalability, maintainability, security, and efficient communication between the user interface and the database.
1. Presentation Layer (Frontend)
The Presentation Layer is responsible for interacting with users and displaying information. It provides a responsive and intuitive interface for devotees and administrators.
Technologies Used
React.js
TypeScript
Tailwind CSS
HTML5
CSS3
Responsibilities
User registration and login
Display temple information
Show available darshan slots
Book and manage tickets
Display booking history
Admin dashboard for managing temples and bookings
Form validation and user interaction

2. Application Layer (Backend)
The Application Layer contains the business logic and handles communication between the frontend and the database through REST APIs.
Technologies Used
Node.js
Express.js
JWT Authentication
RESTful APIs
Responsibilities
User authentication and authorization
Booking validation
Slot availability management
Temple management
Booking confirmation and cancellation
Error handling
API request processing
Data validation

3. Data Layer (Database)
The Data Layer stores all application data securely and ensures data consistency.
Technology Used
MongoDB
Collections
Users
Temples
Darshan Slots
Bookings
Admins
Responsibilities
Store user information
Maintain temple details
Store booking records
Track available time slots
Retrieve booking history
Backup and data integrity

Authentication Architecture
The application uses JSON Web Token (JWT)-based authentication.
User Authentication Flow
User registers using email and password.
Password is securely encrypted before storage.
User logs in with valid credentials.
Backend verifies the credentials.
JWT token is generated.
Token is sent to the frontend.
Frontend includes the token in API requests.
Backend validates the token before granting access to protected resources.

API Architecture
The frontend communicates with the backend using RESTful APIs over HTTP/HTTPS.
Example API Endpoints


Data Flow
User accesses the DarshanEase application.
Frontend sends API requests to the backend.
Backend validates the request.
Business logic processes the request.
MongoDB stores or retrieves data.
Backend returns the response.
Frontend displays updated information to the user.

Security Measures
JWT-based authentication
Password encryption using hashing algorithms
Input validation
Protected API routes
Role-based access control (Admin/User)
Secure database communication
Error and exception handling

